      </task>  
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>\vv = \langle v_1, v_2 \rangle</m> be the vector in <m>\R^2</m> with components <m>v_1</m> and <m>v_2</m> as shown at right in <xref ref="F-9-2-vector-magnitude-a">Figure</xref>. Use the distance formula to find a general formula for <m>\Vert\vv\Vert</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{v}\Vert = \sqrt{(v_1)^2 + (v_2)^2}</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{v}\Vert = \sqrt{(v_1)^2 + (v_2)^2}</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>\vv = \langle v_1, v_2, v_3 \rangle</m> be a vector in <m>\R^3</m>. Use the distance formula to find a general formula for <m>\Vert\vv\Vert</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{v}\Vert = \sqrt{(v_1)^2 + (v_2)^2 + (v_3)^2}</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{v}\Vert = \sqrt{(v_1)^2 + (v_2)^2 + (v_3)^2}</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose that <m>\vu = \langle 2,3\rangle</m> and <m>\vv = \langle -1,2\rangle</m>.  Find <m>\Vert\vu\Vert</m>, <m>\Vert\vv\Vert</m>, and <m>\Vert\vu+\vv\Vert</m>.  Is it true that <m>\Vert\vu + \vv\Vert = \Vert\vu\Vert+\Vert\vv\Vert</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{u}\Vert = \sqrt{13}</m>, <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{v}\Vert = \sqrt{5}</m>, <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{u + v}\Vert = \sqrt{26}</m>, <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{u + v}\Vert != \Vert\overrightarrow{u}\Vert + \Vert\overrightarrow{v}\Vert </m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{u}\Vert = \sqrt{13}</m>, <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{v}\Vert = \sqrt{5}</m>, <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{u + v}\Vert = \sqrt{26}</m>, <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{u + v}\Vert != \Vert\overrightarrow{u}\Vert + \Vert\overrightarrow{v}\Vert </m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Under what conditions will <m>\Vert\vu+\vv\Vert = \Vert\vu\Vert+\Vert\vv\Vert</m>? (Hint: Think about how <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>, and <m>\vu+\vv</m> form the sides of a triangle.)
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{u + v}\Vert = \Vert\overrightarrow{u}\Vert + \Vert\overrightarrow{v}\Vert </m> only if <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m> are scalars of one another.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>, and <m>\vu + \vv</m> form the sides of a triangle. <m>\vu + \vv</m> is the path from the tail of <m>\vu</m> to tip of <m>\vv</m>. The length of <m>\vu + \vv</m> should be shorter than the sum of the lengths of the other sides. The only case where <m>\Vert\vu + \vv\Vert = \Vert\vu\Vert + \Vert\vv\Vert</m> is if the 2 vectors lie on the same ray and have the same direction. This would mean each vector is a scalar of the other vector.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>      
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            With the vector <m>\vu = \langle 2,3\rangle</m>, find the lengths of <m>2\vu</m>, <m>3\vu</m>, and <m>-2\vu</m>, respectively, and use proper notation to label your results.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>2\vu = \langle 4 , 6 \rangle</m>, <m>3\vu = \langle 6 , 9 \rangle</m>, <m>-2\vu = \langle -4 , -6 \rangle</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>2\vu = \langle 4 , 6 \rangle</m>, <m>3\vu = \langle 6 , 9 \rangle</m>, <m>-2\vu = \langle -4 , -6 \rangle</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>t</m> is any scalar, how is <m>\Vert t \vu \Vert</m> related to <m>\Vert \vu \Vert</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\Vertt\vu\Vert = t * \Vert\vu\Vert</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt{(t\vu_1)^2 + (t\vu_2)^2} = \sqrt{t^2(\vu_1)^2 + t^2(\vu_2)^2} = \sqrt{t^2 * ((\vu_1)^2 + (\vu_2)^2)} = t * \sqrt{(\vu_1)^2 + (\vu_2)^2} = t * \Vert\vu\Vert</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>      
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <em>unit vector</em> is a vector whose magnitude is 1. Of the vectors <m>\vi</m>, <m>\vj</m>, and <m>\vi+\vj</m>, which are unit vectors?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\vi</m> and <m>\vj</m> are unit vectors
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\vi</m> is the vector <m>\langle 1, 0 \rangle</m>. This has a magnitude of 1 in the x-direction.
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>\vi</m> is the vector <m>\langle 0, 1 \rangle</m>. This has a magnitude of 1 in the y-direction.
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>\vi + \vj</m> is the vector <m>\langle 1, 0 \rangle + \angle 0, 1 \rangle = \langle 1 ,1 \rangle</m>. This vector has a magnitude of <m>\sqrt{(1)^2 + (1)^2} = \sqrt{2} != 1</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find a unit vector <m>\vv</m> whose direction is the same as <m>\vu = \langle 2, 3\rangle</m>. (Hint: Consider the result of part (g).)
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\langle \frac{2}{\sqrt{13}} , \frac{3}{\sqrt(13)} \rangle</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To find a unit vector in the same direction as <m>\vu</m>, we need to divide <m>\vu</m> by <m>\Vert\vu\Vert</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>\Vert\vu\Vert = \sqrt{(2)^2 + (3)^2} = \sqrt{13}</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The unit vector <m>\vv</m> in the direction of <m>\vu</m> is <m> \sqrt{13} * \langle 2 , 3 \rangle = \langle \frac{2}{\sqrt{13}} , \frac{3}{\sqrt(13)} \rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </activity>
